                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1218">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">833.00N/38½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by President <persName type="from"
                            >Roosevelt</persName> to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-20">May 20,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The enclosed dispatch<note n="1" xml:id="d1218fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                    </note> worries me. Is there some way in which the Ministry of Uruguay in
                    Washington and Mr. Wilson in Montevideo can get word to the Uruguayan Government
                    that the United States is concerned and that it would be a pity for Pan American
                    solidarity if reports of this kind were to get into the public press, whether
                    they are true or not?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>F[<hi rend="smallcaps">rankun</hi>] D. R[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >oosevelt</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
